## Summary of Key Findings

1.  **Enrollment:** Net enrollment rate for children aged 6-14 is 98.8%, with 1.2% not in school.
2.  **Learning Outcomes:** 38.5% of Std III students can read Std II level text, and 63.9% of Std V students can read Std II level text. In arithmetic, 36.9% of Std III students can do subtraction, and 14.8% of Std V students can do division.
3.  **Infrastructure:** Most schools have electricity (90.1%) and drinking water (85.3%). Toilet availability is lower, with 62.4% of schools having useable toilets.
4.  **Teacher Qualifications:** 58.9% of teachers have a graduate degree or above, and 30.2% have a diploma in education.
5.  **School Governance:** 91.5% of schools have an SMC, but only 54.8% held a meeting in the last year.
6.  **Funding:** Most schools receive maintenance and development grants, but TLM grants are largely not received due to policy changes.

## Methodology

The ASER survey is conducted annually by the NGO Pratham. It is a household-based survey that assesses the reading and arithmetic abilities of children aged 5-16. The survey covers all rural districts in India. In Uttarakhand, data was collected from 13 districts. The sample size for Uttarakhand rural is approximately 1,500 households.

## Limitations

1.  The survey is household-based and does not assess children who are not present in the household on the day of the survey.
2.  The reading and arithmetic assessments are simple and may not capture the full range of learning outcomes.
3.  The survey does not cover urban areas.

